<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>You Learned: robots.txt</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <img src="/images/logo.png" alt="EECS Girls Who Tech Camp" class="learn-logo">

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">🤖</div>
      <h1>Challenge 3 Complete!</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">The Robot's Secret</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔍</div>
        <h2>Skill Unlocked</h2>
        <h3>Robots.txt Recon</h3>
        <p><code>robots.txt</code> asks search engines to stay away from certain pages — but it's publicly readable and provides <strong>zero actual security</strong>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🌍</div>
        <h2>Real World</h2>
        <h3>Information Leakage</h3>
        <p>Security pros check <code>robots.txt</code> first during assessments. It often reveals admin panels, staging servers, and backup directories the owner tried to hide.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">👩‍💻</div>
        <h2>Career Path</h2>
        <h3>Bug Bounty Hunter</h3>
        <p>Companies like Google, Apple, and Microsoft pay researchers real money for finding security flaws. Many started as curious teenagers — just like you!</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>Key Takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Obscurity ≠ Security</h3>
        <p>Hiding something doesn't protect it. Real security requires authentication (login), authorization (permissions), and proper access controls.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All Challenges</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %>
      <a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Next Challenge →</a>
      <% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
